On August 23, 2019, the President signed four bills into law. The first bill, H.R. 2336, known as the "Family Farmer Relief Act of 2019," increases the debt limit used to determine if a family farmer is eligible for relief under chapter 12 of the Bankruptcy Code. The second bill, H.R. 2938, known as the "Honoring American Veterans in Extreme Need Act of 2019" or the "HAVEN Act," excludes certain benefits paid by the Department of Veterans Affairs and the Department of Defense from the calculation of monthly income for the Bankruptcy Code's means test. The third bill, H.R. 3304, known as the "National Guard and Reservists Debt Relief Extension Act of 2019," extends the exemption to certain bankruptcy means-testing for members of the National Guard and reserves for the Armed Forces for four years. Lastly, H.R. 3311, known as the "Small Business Reorganization Act of 2019," establishes a subchapter within Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code that allows small business debtors to reorganize using simplified and expedited procedures.